00:24:31,620 --> 00:24:33,120
thereafter, they will stay synchronized.

543
00:24:33,120 --> 00:24:35,620
If you have a whole collection

544
00:24:35,620 --> 00:24:38,120
of synchronized clocks, they will stay synchronized.

545
00:24:38,120 --> 00:24:42,120
That, as we will see, is not true

546
00:24:42,120 --> 00:24:46,120
for moving clocks in the special theory of relativity.

547
00:24:46,120 --> 00:24:50,120
And there's a notion of time which is proper time.

548
00:24:50,120 --> 00:24:52,120
Now here's what proper time means.

549
00:24:52,120 --> 00:24:54,120
It...

550
00:24:54,120 --> 00:24:55,120
You're going to take a walk.

551
00:24:55,120 --> 00:24:56,120
You're going to walk around.

552
00:24:56,120 --> 00:24:57,620
You're going to walk around with a

553
00:24:57,620 --> 00:24:59,120
high velocity, upward near the speed of light.

554
00:24:59,120 --> 00:25:01,120
But you carry your wristwatch with you.

555
00:25:01,120 --> 00:25:02,120
Okay?

556
00:25:02,120 --> 00:25:06,120
Everybody sitting still has their own timepiece.

557
00:25:06,120 --> 00:25:09,120
And the sitting still people all synchronize

558
00:25:09,120 --> 00:25:12,120
their timepieces so that they all agree.

559
00:25:12,120 --> 00:25:15,120
They synchronize their timepieces with light rays.

560
00:25:15,120 --> 00:25:17,120
And according to the way

561
00:25:17,120 --> 00:25:19,120
that Einstein described synchronizing light rays.

562
00:25:19,120 --> 00:25:22,120
So you people all have perfectly synchronized light ray...

563
00:25:22,120 --> 00:25:25,120
Sorry, perfectly synchronized clocks.

564
00:25:25,120 --> 00:25:27,120
And I have my clock.

565
00:25:27,120 --> 00:25:28,120
And I start walking around.

566
00:25:28,120 --> 00:25:29,620
At first when I start,

567
00:25:29,620 --> 00:25:31,120
I synchronize my clock with yours.

568
00:25:31,120 --> 00:25:32,120
We all agree.

569
00:25:32,120 --> 00:25:33,620
And then I walk around and I take

570
00:25:33,620 --> 00:25:35,120
a walk around the table a few times.

571
00:25:35,120 --> 00:25:38,120
At close to the speed of light.

572
00:25:38,120 --> 00:25:39,620
And at the end, I

573
00:25:39,620 --> 00:25:41,120
look at my timepiece and you...

574
00:25:41,120 --> 00:25:43,620
And I compare it with the timepiece of

575
00:25:43,620 --> 00:25:46,120
the person standing next to me over here.

576
00:25:46,120 --> 00:25:48,120
In general, there's no reason for

577
00:25:48,120 --> 00:25:50,120
them to agree and they won't agree.

578
00:25:50,120 --> 00:25:53,120
The proper time of my moving clock...

579
00:25:53,120 --> 00:25:57,120
Is the time read by the moving clock.

580
00:25:57,120 --> 00:25:58,120
Okay?

581
00:25:58,120 --> 00:25:59,120
The coordinate time...

582
00:25:59,120 --> 00:26:00,120
These are definitions.

583
00:26:00,120 --> 00:26:02,620
The coordinate time is the

584
00:26:02,620 --> 00:26:05,120
time measured by your stationary clocks.

585
00:26:05,120 --> 00:26:07,620
So proper time is something which

586
00:26:07,620 --> 00:26:10,120
sort of follows the observer around.

587
00:26:10,120 --> 00:26:14,120
And ticks off intervals of proper time...

588
00:26:14,120 --> 00:26:18,120
As a clock following, as a

589
00:26:18,120 --> 00:26:22,120
wristwatch would tick off instance of time.

590
00:26:23,120 --> 00:26:27,120
Alright, let me give you the formula for proper time.

591
00:26:27,120 --> 00:26:29,120
And then show you that

592
00:26:29,120 --> 00:26:31,120
proper time is an invariant concept.

593
00:26:31,120 --> 00:26:34,120
The proper time between two events.

594
00:26:34,120 --> 00:26:35,120
We're talking about now two events.

595
00:26:35,120 --> 00:26:37,620
We could think of them as two

596
00:26:37,620 --> 00:26:40,120
events along a trajectory if we wanted.

597
00:26:40,120 --> 00:26:43,120
The trajectory could be the trajectory of a moving clock.

598
00:26:43,120 --> 00:26:45,120
But for the moment, let's just

599
00:26:45,120 --> 00:26:47,120
think of them as two events.

600
00:26:47,120 --> 00:26:49,120
And one of them, for

601
00:26:49,120 --> 00:26:51,120
simplicity, let's take at the origin.

602
00:26:53,120 --> 00:26:56,120
So the origin of coordinates.

603
00:26:56,120 --> 00:26:58,620
So this point over here is x equals 0, t

604
00:26:58,620 --> 00:27:01,120
equals 0, x prime equals 0, t prime equals 0.

605
00:27:01,120 --> 00:27:04,120
Notice, incidentally, where's our Lorentz transformation?

606
00:27:04,120 --> 00:27:06,120
We seem to have lost them.

607
00:27:06,120 --> 00:27:08,120
Let me write them back over here.

608
00:27:08,120 --> 00:27:10,120
x equals x minus v...

609
00:27:10,120 --> 00:27:13,120
x prime equals x minus vt over

610
00:27:13,120 --> 00:27:16,120
square root of 1 minus v squared.

611
00:27:16,120 --> 00:27:19,120
t prime is equal to t minus

612
00:27:19,120 --> 00:27:22,120
vx over root 1 minus v squared.

613
00:27:23,120 --> 00:27:26,620
Notice that when x and t are both equal to

614
00:27:26,620 --> 00:27:30,120
0, x prime and t prime are also equal to 0.

615
00:27:30,120 --> 00:27:33,620
So we set it up in such a way that

616
00:27:33,620 --> 00:27:37,120
the origin of space-time coordinates is the same for both observers.

617
00:27:37,120 --> 00:27:42,120
Okay, so here's our moving observer.

618
00:27:42,120 --> 00:27:44,120
Or let this not even be a moving observer.

619
00:27:44,120 --> 00:27:47,120
It's just a moving particle or moving person.

620
00:27:47,120 --> 00:27:52,120
It doesn't have to correspond to a reference frame.

621
00:27:52,120 --> 00:27:54,120
It's just some object moving.

622
00:27:54,120 --> 00:27:58,120
And it could be moving with an accelerated velocity,

623
00:27:58,120 --> 00:28:01,620
but let's just take a small piece of its trajectory

624
00:28:01,620 --> 00:28:05,120
along which we can approximate it by a straight line.

625
00:28:05,120 --> 00:28:06,120
Okay.

626
00:28:06,120 --> 00:28:15,120
Now, if we replaced space-time by ordinary space...

627
00:28:15,120 --> 00:28:17,120
If we replaced it by ordinary space,

628
00:28:17,120 --> 00:28:19,120
forget this and just think about ordinary space.

629
00:28:19,120 --> 00:28:22,120
Not x and t, but x and y.

630
00:28:22,120 --> 00:28:27,620
We could also have different coordinates describing

631
00:28:27,620 --> 00:28:33,120
the same x prime and y prime,

632
00:28:33,120 --> 00:28:35,620
namely coordinates which were just

633
00:28:35,620 --> 00:28:38,120
rotated relative to the original coordinates.

634
00:28:38,120 --> 00:28:43,120
What kinds of things are the same for both...

635
00:28:43,120 --> 00:28:45,120
I'll call them observers, but

636
00:28:45,120 --> 00:28:47,120
I simply mean rotated coordinate frames.

637
00:28:47,120 --> 00:28:49,620
Well, one very invariant quantity is

638
00:28:49,620 --> 00:28:52,120
the distance from the original coordinate frame.

639
00:28:52,120 --> 00:28:57,620
The distance from the origin of any point

640
00:28:57,620 --> 00:29:03,120
necessarily is the same in both coordinate frames.

641
00:29:03,120 --> 00:29:05,120
That's clear.

642
00:29:05,120 --> 00:29:07,620
Your distance from me doesn't

643
00:29:07,620 --> 00:29:10,120
depend on which way I'm oriented.

644
00:29:10,120 --> 00:29:12,120
I have my x and my y.

645
00:29:12,120 --> 00:29:14,120
It doesn't matter which way I'm oriented.

646
00:29:14,120 --> 00:29:17,120
You're still sitting three meters or three or four

647
00:29:17,120 --> 00:29:20,120
meters from me, no matter which way I turn.

648
00:29:20,120 --> 00:29:22,620
So that implies that the

649
00:29:22,620 --> 00:29:25,120
distance from the origin, the square...

650
00:29:25,120 --> 00:29:27,120
Let's take the square of the distance

651
00:29:27,120 --> 00:29:29,120
from the origin, call it s squared.

652
00:29:29,120 --> 00:29:33,120
That's equal to x squared plus y squared.

653
00:29:33,120 --> 00:29:37,120
It must also be equal to

654
00:29:37,120 --> 00:29:41,120
x prime squared plus y prime squared.

655
00:29:41,120 --> 00:29:44,620
In other words, the quantity x squared plus

656
00:29:44,620 --> 00:29:48,120
y squared is the same in any coordinate system,

657
00:29:48,120 --> 00:29:49,120
ordinary coordinate system,

658
00:29:49,120 --> 00:29:52,120
involving the rotation of coordinates.

659
00:29:52,120 --> 00:29:56,120
Something like that is true for Lorentz transformations.

660
00:29:56,120 --> 00:29:58,620
Something slightly different, a

661
00:29:58,620 --> 00:30:01,120
little slightly different mathematical expression.

662
00:30:01,120 --> 00:30:04,120
This is x, this is t.

663
00:30:04,120 --> 00:30:08,620
And this is some point here with

664
00:30:08,620 --> 00:30:13,120
coordinates x, t or x prime, t prime,

665
00:30:13,120 --> 00:30:15,620
depending on which frame of

666
00:30:15,620 --> 00:30:18,120
reference I'm looking at that event.

667
00:30:19,120 --> 00:30:21,120
The statement which we can

668
00:30:21,120 --> 00:30:23,120
work out from this equation here...

669
00:30:23,120 --> 00:30:24,120
In fact, let's do it.

670
00:30:24,120 --> 00:30:26,120
Let's do it.

671
00:30:26,120 --> 00:30:30,120
Let's take the point x, t, which

672
00:30:30,120 --> 00:30:34,120
could also be labeled by the prime coordinates,

673
00:30:34,120 --> 00:30:39,120
and work out the quantity x prime squared,

674
00:30:39,120 --> 00:30:43,120
not t prime squared plus x prime squared,

675
00:30:43,120 --> 00:30:47,120
but t prime squared minus x prime squared.

676
00:30:47,120 --> 00:30:50,620
So, we have a little bit of a glitch on

677
00:30:50,620 --> 00:30:54,120
what we would do if we were just rotating coordinates.

678
00:30:54,120 --> 00:30:56,120
t prime squared minus x prime squared.

679
00:30:56,120 --> 00:30:58,120
Let's write it on the right here.

680
00:30:58,120 --> 00:31:00,120
First of all, in the denominator,

681
00:31:00,120 --> 00:31:02,120
we'll get 1 minus v squared,

682
00:31:02,120 --> 00:31:05,120
because we've squared everything.

683
00:31:05,120 --> 00:31:07,120
All right, now let's look at x prime squared.

684
00:31:07,120 --> 00:31:10,120
That has x squared.

685
00:31:10,120 --> 00:31:15,120
It has plus v squared t squared.

686
00:31:15,120 --> 00:31:22,120
Minus 2 x v t.

687
00:31:22,120 --> 00:31:25,120
That's...oh, that's x prime squared, huh?

688
00:31:25,120 --> 00:31:28,120
That comes in with a minus sign here.

689
00:31:28,120 --> 00:31:30,120
But then let's add in t prime squared.

690
00:31:30,120 --> 00:31:35,620
t prime squared has t squared plus v

691
00:31:35,620 --> 00:31:41,120
squared x squared minus 2 x v t,

692
00:31:41,120 --> 00:31:44,120
also divided by 1 minus v squared.

693
00:31:45,120 --> 00:31:49,120
All right, so this is t prime squared.

694
00:31:49,120 --> 00:31:52,120
This is x prime squared, and we subtract them.

695
00:31:52,120 --> 00:31:55,620
The first thing that we notice is

696
00:31:55,620 --> 00:31:59,120
that these things, these cross terms, cancel.

697
00:31:59,120 --> 00:32:04,120
When we subtract these two, the cross terms cancel.

698
00:32:04,120 --> 00:32:08,120
Now, the x squares don't cancel,

699
00:32:08,120 --> 00:32:10,620
because here we have v

700
00:32:10,620 --> 00:32:13,120
squared x squared minus x squared.

701
00:32:13,120 --> 00:32:14,120
All right?

702
00:32:14,120 --> 00:32:23,120
So that's minus 1 minus v squared x squared.

703
00:32:23,120 --> 00:32:25,120
And then what about the t squared term?

704
00:32:25,120 --> 00:32:32,120
There's t squared here minus v squared t squared.

705
00:32:32,120 --> 00:32:37,120
So that's t squared times 1 minus v squared,

706
00:32:37,120 --> 00:32:41,120
all over 1 minus v squared.

707
00:32:41,120 --> 00:32:43,120
To make a long story short,

708
00:32:43,120 --> 00:32:45,120
let's write it out.

709
00:32:45,120 --> 00:32:49,120
t prime squared minus x prime squared

710
00:32:49,120 --> 00:32:53,120
is equal to t squared minus x squared.

711
00:32:53,120 --> 00:32:54,120
Just work it out.

712
00:32:54,120 --> 00:32:58,120
If you didn't follow a little bit of algebra here,

713
00:32:58,120 --> 00:32:59,120
just work it out.

714
00:32:59,120 --> 00:33:04,120
Square this, square this, subtract them in either way,

715
00:33:04,120 --> 00:33:06,120
and you'll find out that t

716
00:33:06,120 --> 00:33:08,120
prime squared minus x prime squared

717
00:33:08,120 --> 00:33:11,120
is the same as t squared minus x squared.

718
00:33:11,120 --> 00:33:12,120
Very, very much.

719
00:33:13,120 --> 00:33:18,120
Like when you rotate coordinates,

720
00:33:18,120 --> 00:33:21,120
the square of the distance stays the same.

721
00:33:21,120 --> 00:33:22,120
The square of the distance

722
00:33:22,120 --> 00:33:23,120
from the origin stays the same.

723
00:33:23,120 --> 00:33:30,120
Now, a physicist would say that means that the quantity

724
00:33:30,120 --> 00:33:33,120
t squared minus x squared is invariant.

725
00:33:33,120 --> 00:33:36,120
It's the same no matter whether you look at it

726
00:33:36,120 --> 00:33:38,120
from the point of view of

727
00:33:38,120 --> 00:33:40,120
the primed frame or the unprimed frame.

728
00:33:40,120 --> 00:33:41,120
And it has a name.

729
00:33:41,120 --> 00:33:44,120
Because it's invariant, it's important.

730
00:33:44,120 --> 00:33:46,120
Anything which is invariant and which

731
00:33:46,120 --> 00:33:48,120
is the same for all observers

732
00:33:48,120 --> 00:33:51,120
must have a special importance.

733
00:33:51,120 --> 00:33:55,120
It's something which everybody will agree upon,

734
00:33:55,120 --> 00:33:57,120
and so we ought to give it a name.

735
00:33:57,120 --> 00:34:00,120
The name for it is proper time.

736
00:34:00,120 --> 00:34:04,120
The proper time between this point and this point.

737
00:34:04,120 --> 00:34:05,120
Proper time.

738
00:34:05,120 --> 00:34:10,120
The proper time between the origin

739
00:34:10,120 --> 00:34:19,120
and the point is by definition, proper time,

740
00:34:19,120 --> 00:34:23,120
is equal to the square root

741
00:34:23,120 --> 00:34:27,120
of t squared minus x squared.

742
00:34:27,120 --> 00:34:28,120
Why the square root?

743
00:34:28,120 --> 00:34:30,120
Well, it's very similar to the...

744
00:34:30,120 --> 00:34:32,120
It's a definition, of course.

745
00:34:32,120 --> 00:34:33,120
It's a definition.

746
00:34:33,120 --> 00:34:34,120
We could have worked with

747
00:34:34,120 --> 00:34:35,120
a definition where the proper time

748
00:34:35,120 --> 00:34:38,120
was just t squared minus x squared,

749
00:34:38,120 --> 00:34:39,120
but it's a definition.

750
00:34:39,120 --> 00:34:40,120
Take a look.

751
00:34:40,120 --> 00:34:41,120
Take a look at the square root.

752
00:34:41,120 --> 00:34:42,620
But it's very much like looking

753
00:34:42,620 --> 00:34:44,120
at the distance between two points

754
00:34:44,120 --> 00:34:46,120
and using Pythagoras' theorem.

755
00:34:46,120 --> 00:34:48,120
The Pythagorean theorem says that

756
00:34:48,120 --> 00:34:50,120
the distance between the points

757
00:34:50,120 --> 00:34:54,120
is the square root of x squared plus y squared.

758
00:34:54,120 --> 00:34:56,120
All right, so in parallel with that,

759
00:34:56,120 --> 00:35:00,120
we call this the proper time between

760
00:35:00,120 --> 00:35:04,120
the origin and the point x, t.

761
00:35:04,120 --> 00:35:06,120
And that, as I said, is definition,

762
00:35:06,120 --> 00:35:08,120
but it's a highly useful definition,

763
00:35:08,120 --> 00:35:10,120
and we'll see why it's useful as we go along.

764
00:35:10,120 --> 00:35:12,120
But the main thing about it

765
00:35:12,120 --> 00:35:14,120
is that everybody agrees about it.

766
00:35:14,120 --> 00:35:18,120
Okay, first of all, let's look at some possible values

767
00:35:18,120 --> 00:35:21,120
that the proper time can

768
00:35:21,120 --> 00:35:24,120
have for various points, x, t.

769
00:35:24,120 --> 00:35:27,120
If t is bigger than x,

770
00:35:27,120 --> 00:35:29,120
what does it mean for

771
00:35:29,120 --> 00:35:31,120
t to be bigger than x?

772
00:35:31,120 --> 00:35:35,120
In magnitude, if t squared is bigger than x squared.

773
00:35:35,120 --> 00:35:38,120
If t squared is bigger than x squared,

774
00:35:38,120 --> 00:35:43,120
that means we're talking about points

775
00:35:43,120 --> 00:35:46,120
which are in a wedge here,

776
00:35:46,120 --> 00:35:50,120
where time, where the time component

777
00:35:50,120 --> 00:35:52,120
is larger than the x component.

778
00:35:52,120 --> 00:35:55,120
t squared is larger than x squared,

779
00:35:55,120 --> 00:35:58,120
all in here.

780
00:35:58,120 --> 00:36:00,120
But let's, in particular, stay

781
00:36:00,120 --> 00:36:02,120
in the upper half space here.

782
00:36:02,120 --> 00:36:04,120
t squared is bigger than x squared

783
00:36:04,120 --> 00:36:07,120
if you're within this wedge.

784
00:36:08,120 --> 00:36:11,120
The wedge is the light cone.

785
00:36:11,120 --> 00:36:13,120
Oh, I should add in,

786
00:36:13,120 --> 00:36:15,120
yes, I should add something in.

787
00:36:15,120 --> 00:36:18,120
If we are working in three dimensions,

788
00:36:18,120 --> 00:36:21,120
not, sorry, three spatial dimensions,

789
00:36:21,120 --> 00:36:23,120
not one spatial dimension,

790
00:36:23,120 --> 00:36:25,120
then we should also add in

791
00:36:25,120 --> 00:36:27,120
minus y squared minus z squared here.

792
00:36:27,120 --> 00:36:32,120
Minus y prime squared minus z prime squared.

793
00:36:32,120 --> 00:36:36,120
That's the first thing.

794
00:36:36,120 --> 00:36:40,120
That makes sure that our definitions

795
00:36:40,120 --> 00:36:43,120
don't depend on direction and space.

796
00:36:43,120 --> 00:36:45,120
As long as we know that we're only talking about

797
00:36:45,120 --> 00:36:47,120
Lorentz transformations along a given axis,

798
00:36:47,120 --> 00:36:50,120
we don't really have to worry about y and z.

799
00:36:50,120 --> 00:36:52,120
But if we wanted to do Lorentz transformations

800
00:36:52,120 --> 00:36:53,120
along some other axis,

801
00:36:53,120 --> 00:36:55,120
and we wanted to add in y and z,

802
00:36:55,120 --> 00:36:58,120
we would note that this whole quantity,

803
00:36:58,120 --> 00:36:59,620
t prime squared minus x

804
00:36:59,620 --> 00:37:01,120
prime squared minus y prime squared

805
00:37:01,120 --> 00:37:03,120
minus z prime squared is invariant.

806
00:37:03,120 --> 00:37:05,120
Why is that incidentally?

807
00:37:05,120 --> 00:37:09,120
Well, remember that z prime and y prime don't transform

808
00:37:09,120 --> 00:37:11,120
when we go from one frame of

809
00:37:11,120 --> 00:37:13,120
reference along the x axis to another.

810
00:37:13,120 --> 00:37:15,120
And so that doesn't make any difference

811
00:37:15,120 --> 00:37:17,120
if we put in y prime and z prime here,

812
00:37:17,120 --> 00:37:19,120
but it's a convenience to add it in,

813
00:37:19,120 --> 00:37:21,120
and then we have an expression here

814
00:37:21,120 --> 00:37:24,120
which doesn't depend on direction and space.

815
00:37:24,120 --> 00:37:26,120
But if you only want to think more simply

816
00:37:26,120 --> 00:37:30,120
about directions along a single axis,

817
00:37:30,120 --> 00:37:32,120
then you don't have to worry about y and z.

818
00:37:32,120 --> 00:37:33,120
Okay.

819
00:37:33,120 --> 00:37:34,120
So here we are.

820
00:37:34,120 --> 00:37:36,120
This point here,

821
00:37:36,120 --> 00:37:40,120
t squared is greater than x squared,

822
00:37:40,120 --> 00:37:42,120
and that means that t

823
00:37:42,120 --> 00:37:44,120
squared minus x squared is positive,

824
00:37:44,120 --> 00:37:46,120
and the square root of a positive number

825
00:37:46,120 --> 00:37:51,120
is another real number.

826
00:37:51,120 --> 00:37:55,120
So in this time-like region,

827
00:37:55,120 --> 00:37:57,120
this is called the time-like region

828
00:37:57,120 --> 00:38:01,120
because the coordinates are more in the direction of time

829
00:38:01,120 --> 00:38:03,120
than they are in space,

830
00:38:03,120 --> 00:38:05,120
and in the time-like region,

831
00:38:05,120 --> 00:38:09,120
the proper time is just a positive number,

832
00:38:09,120 --> 00:38:11,120
square root of a positive number,

833
00:38:11,120 --> 00:38:13,120
and we take the positive square root.

834
00:38:13,120 --> 00:38:15,120
So t squared, so that's perfectly normal.

835
00:38:15,120 --> 00:38:18,120
Positive proper time up in here.

836
00:38:18,120 --> 00:38:21,120
What about along the light cone?

837
00:38:21,120 --> 00:38:23,120
Along the light cone,

838
00:38:23,120 --> 00:38:27,120
that's exactly where x is either equal to t

839
00:38:27,120 --> 00:38:29,120
or x is equal to minus t.

840
00:38:29,120 --> 00:38:31,120
Along here, x is equal to t.

841
00:38:31,120 --> 00:38:33,120
Along here, x is equal to minus t.

842
00:38:33,120 --> 00:38:35,120
Oops.

843
00:38:35,120 --> 00:38:37,120
x is equal to minus t.

844
00:38:37,120 --> 00:38:40,120
So in either case,

845
00:38:40,120 --> 00:38:44,120
t squared is equal to x squared.

846
00:38:44,120 --> 00:38:46,120
So along the light cone,

847
00:38:46,120 --> 00:38:49,120
along the place where light rays can travel,

848
00:38:49,120 --> 00:38:51,120
the proper distance between,

849
00:38:51,120 --> 00:38:53,120
or the proper time between the

850
00:38:53,120 --> 00:38:55,120
origin and that point is zero.

851
00:38:55,120 --> 00:38:57,120
Now, this is a big difference

852
00:38:57,120 --> 00:39:01,120
between ordinary distance and proper time.

853
00:39:01,120 --> 00:39:02,120
Ordinary distance,

854
00:39:02,120 --> 00:39:05,120
if the distance between two points is zero,

855
00:39:05,120 --> 00:39:08,120
those points are the same point.

856
00:39:08,120 --> 00:39:10,120
There's no way that the distance

857
00:39:10,120 --> 00:39:12,120
between two points can be zero

858
00:39:12,120 --> 00:39:15,120
and then not be sitting on top of each other.

859
00:39:15,120 --> 00:39:17,120
In Minkowski space,

860
00:39:17,120 --> 00:39:20,120
in the space describing the special theory of relativity,

861
00:39:20,120 --> 00:39:22,120
the space-time,

862
00:39:22,120 --> 00:39:25,120
two points can have zero proper distance between them

863
00:39:25,120 --> 00:39:28,120
or zero proper time between them

864
00:39:28,120 --> 00:39:30,120
and still not be the same point,

865
00:39:30,120 --> 00:39:31,120
here and here.

866
00:39:31,120 --> 00:39:34,120
What is true

867
00:39:34,120 --> 00:39:36,120
is that if two points

868
00:39:36,120 --> 00:39:38,120
are separated by zero proper time,

869
00:39:38,120 --> 00:39:40,120
then a light ray can

870
00:39:40,120 --> 00:39:42,120
go from one to the other.

871
00:39:42,120 --> 00:39:45,120
So the trajectories of light rays

872
00:39:45,120 --> 00:39:47,120
correspond to paths

873
00:39:47,120 --> 00:39:49,120
which

874
00:39:49,120 --> 00:39:54,120
have essentially zero proper time along them.

875
00:39:54,120 --> 00:39:57,120
Real particles,

876
00:39:57,120 --> 00:39:58,120
sorry, not real particles,

877
00:39:58,120 --> 00:39:59,120
but mass,

878
00:39:59,120 --> 00:40:01,120
but particles moving with less than the speed

879
00:40:01,120 --> 00:40:03,120
of light,

880
00:40:03,120 --> 00:40:04,120
have trajectories

881
00:40:04,120 --> 00:40:07,120
which are in the time-like direction like that.

882
00:40:07,120 --> 00:40:09,120
They're moving slower than the speed of light

883
00:40:09,120 --> 00:40:13,120
and the proper time along those is positive.

884
00:40:13,120 --> 00:40:17,120
Now, let me prove a simple thing.

885
00:40:17,120 --> 00:40:21,120
Proper time

886
00:40:21,120 --> 00:40:24,120
measures

887
00:40:24,120 --> 00:40:27,120
ordinary time as seen by

888
00:40:27,120 --> 00:40:30,120
a clock moving with the object.

889
00:40:30,120 --> 00:40:31,120
For example,

890
00:40:31,120 --> 00:40:34,120
supposing we have a clock which is at rest.

891
00:40:34,120 --> 00:40:37,120
A clock which is at rest in our frame

892
00:40:37,120 --> 00:40:39,120
just has a vertical world line.

893
00:40:39,120 --> 00:40:42,120
It's perfectly at rest.

894
00:40:42,120 --> 00:40:46,120
And for such a point,

895
00:40:46,120 --> 00:40:48,120
let's take a point along here,

896
00:40:48,120 --> 00:40:51,120
what's the proper time from the origin?

897
00:40:51,120 --> 00:40:55,120
It's the square root of t squared minus x squared,

898
00:40:55,120 --> 00:40:58,120
but x is zero for this point.

899
00:40:58,120 --> 00:41:00,120
So it's just the square root of t squared,

900
00:41:00,120 --> 00:41:02,120
which is just t.

901
00:41:02,120 --> 00:41:05,120
So the proper time along a trajectory

902
00:41:05,120 --> 00:41:07,120
which is standing still

903
00:41:07,120 --> 00:41:10,120
is just the ordinary time.

904
00:41:10,120 --> 00:41:12,120
What does that tell you?

905
00:41:12,120 --> 00:41:15,120
That tells you that the proper time

906
00:41:15,120 --> 00:41:18,120
is nothing but the time read by a wristwatch

907
00:41:18,120 --> 00:41:20,120
standing still.

908
00:41:20,120 --> 00:41:22,120
What about,

909
00:41:22,120 --> 00:41:24,120
what about the proper time

910
00:41:24,120 --> 00:41:27,120
along a trajectory which has a finite velocity?

911
00:41:27,120 --> 00:41:31,120
For example, supposing it has a finite velocity like that,

912
00:41:31,120 --> 00:41:34,120
and we look at the proper time

913
00:41:34,120 --> 00:41:37,120
for a particular point over here.

914
00:41:37,120 --> 00:41:39,120
Well,

915
00:41:39,120 --> 00:41:41,120
the principle of relativity,

916
00:41:41,120 --> 00:41:43,120
the equivalence between different reference frames,

917
00:41:43,120 --> 00:41:45,120
tells us the following thing.

918
00:41:45,120 --> 00:41:48,120
We could always think

919
00:41:48,120 --> 00:41:51,120
of this

920
00:41:51,120 --> 00:41:53,120
particle, object, observer

921
00:41:53,120 --> 00:41:55,120
as being at rest.

922
00:41:55,120 --> 00:41:57,120
We could always do a Lorentz equation,

923
00:41:57,120 --> 00:41:59,120
a Lorentz transformation.

924
00:41:59,120 --> 00:42:02,120
So this guy is the guy at rest,

925
00:42:02,120 --> 00:42:04,120
and then use the same logic

926
00:42:04,120 --> 00:42:06,120
that we used a second ago.

927
00:42:06,120 --> 00:42:09,120
In the reference frame where this is at rest,

928
00:42:09,120 --> 00:42:13,120
this point here would have x prime equals zero,

929
00:42:13,120 --> 00:42:16,120
but t prime not equal to zero.

930
00:42:16,120 --> 00:42:19,120
Why is it x prime equal to zero?

931
00:42:19,120 --> 00:42:21,120
Because

932
00:42:21,120 --> 00:42:23,120
in the moving reference frame,

933
00:42:23,120 --> 00:42:25,120
moving with this guy over here,

934
00:42:25,120 --> 00:42:27,620
this whole trajectory corresponds

935
00:42:27,620 --> 00:42:30,120
to his origin of coordinates.

936
00:42:30,120 --> 00:42:32,120
So x prime would be zero

937
00:42:32,120 --> 00:42:34,120
for somebody moving along this trajectory here,

938
00:42:34,120 --> 00:42:37,120
but t prime would not be zero over here.

939
00:42:37,120 --> 00:42:40,120
And we could work out exactly the same argument.

940
00:42:40,120 --> 00:42:43,120
The proper time to this point over here

941
00:42:43,120 --> 00:42:48,120
would be t prime squared minus x prime squared,

942
00:42:48,120 --> 00:42:50,120
but x prime squared is zero.

943
00:42:50,120 --> 00:42:53,120
And so the proper time along here,

944
00:42:53,120 --> 00:42:55,120
in the same way as along here,

945
00:42:55,120 --> 00:42:58,120
as along the vertical trajectory,

946
00:42:58,120 --> 00:43:00,120
measures the time

947
00:43:00,120 --> 00:43:02,120
as read by a moving watch,

948
00:43:02,120 --> 00:43:04,120
a moving clock.

949
00:43:04,120 --> 00:43:07,120
Moving clocks tick off proper time.

950
00:43:10,120 --> 00:43:12,120
That's the message.

951
00:43:12,120 --> 00:43:14,120
That the meaning of proper time

952
00:43:14,120 --> 00:43:16,120
is nothing but the meaning of the time

953
00:43:16,120 --> 00:43:18,120
as read by a watch

954
00:43:18,120 --> 00:43:22,120
which is moving with the moving object.

955
00:43:22,120 --> 00:43:25,120
So that's the notion of proper time.

956
00:43:25,120 --> 00:43:27,120
It's kind of funny,

957
00:43:27,120 --> 00:43:29,120
in these regions over here,

958
00:43:29,120 --> 00:43:31,120
in these regions over here,

959
00:43:31,120 --> 00:43:33,120
x is bigger than t,

960
00:43:33,120 --> 00:43:36,120
and so t squared minus x squared is negative,

961
00:43:36,120 --> 00:43:39,120
and the proper time is imaginary.

962
00:43:39,120 --> 00:43:42,120
Points up in here are called time-like,

963
00:43:42,120 --> 00:43:44,120
relative to the origin.

964
00:43:44,120 --> 00:43:46,120
Points along the light cone here

965
00:43:46,120 --> 00:43:48,120
are called light-like,

966
00:43:48,120 --> 00:43:50,120
and points out here are called time-like.

967
00:43:50,120 --> 00:43:51,120
So,

968
00:43:51,120 --> 00:43:54,120
points out here are called space-like.

969
00:43:54,120 --> 00:43:58,120
Space-like points have an imaginary proper distance,

970
00:43:58,120 --> 00:44:02,120
an imaginary proper time relative to the origin,

971
00:44:02,120 --> 00:44:03,120
but points in the,

972
00:44:03,120 --> 00:44:04,120
within the light cone,

973
00:44:04,120 --> 00:44:06,120
have a real proper time.

974
00:44:06,120 --> 00:44:08,120
Okay, any questions about

975
00:44:08,120 --> 00:44:10,120
the notion of proper time?

976
00:44:10,120 --> 00:44:14,120
It's very similar to distance along a trajectory,

977
00:44:14,120 --> 00:44:16,120
except with a funny property

978
00:44:16,120 --> 00:44:19,120
that there's a minus sign that you throw in here.

979
00:44:19,120 --> 00:44:20,120
A minus sign that you throw in,

980
00:44:20,120 --> 00:44:23,120
instead of a plus sign.

981
00:44:23,120 --> 00:44:26,120
t squared minus x squared.

982
00:44:26,120 --> 00:44:29,120
But it has many similar properties,

983
00:44:29,120 --> 00:44:30,120
and in particular,

984
00:44:30,120 --> 00:44:32,120
it's the same in every reference frame.

985
00:44:32,120 --> 00:44:35,120
The proper time between two distinct points

986
00:44:35,120 --> 00:44:38,120
is invariant.

987
00:44:38,120 --> 00:44:40,120
Okay.

988
00:44:40,120 --> 00:44:41,120
Now,

989
00:44:41,120 --> 00:44:43,120
we can use that fact.

990
00:44:43,120 --> 00:44:45,120
We can use that fact,

991
00:44:45,120 --> 00:44:47,120
and facts similar to it,

992
00:44:47,120 --> 00:44:49,120
well, that...

993
00:44:49,120 --> 00:44:53,120
The time interval between two points.

994
00:44:53,120 --> 00:44:56,120
The time interval as read by a clock

995
00:44:56,120 --> 00:44:59,120
that moves between those two points.

996
00:44:59,120 --> 00:45:00,120
Well, yeah, it's just,

997
00:45:00,120 --> 00:45:01,120
you were using the same,

998
00:45:01,120 --> 00:45:03,120
you were using the same word for both interval

999
00:45:03,120 --> 00:45:06,120
and reading the clock.

1000
00:45:06,120 --> 00:45:08,120
Uh...

1001
00:45:08,120 --> 00:45:09,120
Never mind.

1002
00:45:09,120 --> 00:45:11,120
Okay.

1003
00:45:11,120 --> 00:45:13,120
I meant time interval, but,

1004
00:45:13,120 --> 00:45:15,120
yeah.

1005
00:45:15,120 --> 00:45:16,120
Yeah.

1006
00:45:16,120 --> 00:45:18,120
So, to put it another way,

1007
00:45:18,120 --> 00:45:21,120
if there are two points in space-time,

1008
00:45:21,120 --> 00:45:22,120
and a clock,

1009
00:45:22,120 --> 00:45:24,120
a physical real clock,

1010
00:45:24,120 --> 00:45:26,120
can move from one to the other

1011
00:45:26,120 --> 00:45:28,120
along a straight trajectory,

1012
00:45:28,120 --> 00:45:31,120
that means a trajectory with constant velocity,

1013
00:45:31,120 --> 00:45:34,120
then the difference of time readings

1014
00:45:34,120 --> 00:45:36,120
at the two ends of the trajectory over here

1015
00:45:36,120 --> 00:45:38,120
will be the proper time.

1016
00:45:38,120 --> 00:45:39,120
In other words,

1017
00:45:39,120 --> 00:45:40,120
the distance,

1018
00:45:40,120 --> 00:45:42,120
the difference between the time read at this point

1019
00:45:42,120 --> 00:45:43,120
and at that point

1020
00:45:43,120 --> 00:45:46,120
will be the proper time along that trajectory.

1021
00:45:46,120 --> 00:45:47,120
You can calculate that,

1022
00:45:47,120 --> 00:45:48,120
you can calculate then,

1023
00:45:48,120 --> 00:45:52,120
if I give you two points in space-time,

1024
00:45:52,120 --> 00:45:54,120
we can calculate very easily

1025
00:45:54,120 --> 00:45:57,120
how long it takes to move between these two points

1026
00:45:57,120 --> 00:46:00,120
as read by the moving clock.

1027
00:46:00,120 --> 00:46:02,120
Not as read by stationary clocks.

1028
00:46:02,120 --> 00:46:03,120
That's different.

1029
00:46:03,120 --> 00:46:05,120
As read by stationary clocks,

1030
00:46:05,120 --> 00:46:07,120
the time difference is just

1031
00:46:07,120 --> 00:46:09,120
whatever the time was at this point

1032
00:46:09,120 --> 00:46:11,120
and whatever the time was at this point,

1033
00:46:11,120 --> 00:46:13,120
where the times were just, um,

1034
00:46:13,120 --> 00:46:15,120
t.

1035
00:46:15,120 --> 00:46:17,120
But the moving clock,

1036
00:46:17,120 --> 00:46:20,120
the moving clock reads its own time.

1037
00:46:23,120 --> 00:46:26,120
That's the message of special relativity,

1038
00:46:26,120 --> 00:46:28,120
that the rate at which clocks move

1039
00:46:28,120 --> 00:46:30,120
depends on how they move.

1040
00:46:30,120 --> 00:46:32,120
Now we can work out,

1041
00:46:32,120 --> 00:46:34,120
in some detail,

1042
00:46:34,120 --> 00:46:36,120
the relationship between moving clocks

1043
00:46:36,120 --> 00:46:37,120
and stationary clocks.

1044
00:46:37,120 --> 00:46:38,120
Let's do that.

1045
00:46:38,120 --> 00:46:41,120
And the tool is to use proper time.

1046
00:46:41,120 --> 00:46:43,120
So,

1047
00:46:43,120 --> 00:46:46,120
let's take a clock,

1048
00:46:47,120 --> 00:46:50,120
which starts at the origin,

1049
00:46:50,120 --> 00:46:53,120
and moves along a trajectory,

1050
00:46:53,120 --> 00:46:55,120
which takes it to a point,

1051
00:46:55,120 --> 00:46:57,120
let's call,

1052
00:46:57,120 --> 00:46:59,120
which takes it to a point,

1053
00:46:59,120 --> 00:47:02,120
on the origin of the moving coordinates.

1054
00:47:02,120 --> 00:47:03,120
I'm sorry,

1055
00:47:03,120 --> 00:47:05,120
that line does not look very straight, does it?

1056
00:47:05,120 --> 00:47:08,120
I intended it to be a straight line.

1057
00:47:09,120 --> 00:47:13,120
Here we have our moving coordinate frame,

1058
00:47:13,120 --> 00:47:16,120
and a clock moves from the origin,

1059
00:47:17,120 --> 00:47:18,120
to a point over here.

1060
00:47:18,120 --> 00:47:20,120
Now what is that point over here?

1061
00:47:20,120 --> 00:47:23,120
That point over here is x prime equals zero.

1062
00:47:25,120 --> 00:47:27,120
It's the origin of spatial coordinates

1063
00:47:27,120 --> 00:47:29,120
for the moving observer.

1064
00:47:29,120 --> 00:47:31,120
And,

1065
00:47:31,120 --> 00:47:34,120
it's some point, t prime.

1066
00:47:35,120 --> 00:47:38,120
It also has coordinates,

1067
00:47:38,120 --> 00:47:41,120
x, t.

1068
00:47:41,120 --> 00:47:44,120
In other words, in the stationary reference frame,

1069
00:47:44,120 --> 00:47:46,120
it has coordinates x, t,

1070
00:47:46,120 --> 00:47:48,120
in the moving frame,

1071
00:47:48,120 --> 00:47:51,120
it has coordinates x prime equals zero,

1072
00:47:51,120 --> 00:47:53,120
and some t prime.

1073
00:47:53,120 --> 00:47:55,120
I would like to know,

1074
00:47:55,120 --> 00:47:58,120
if I know x and I know t,

1075
00:47:58,120 --> 00:48:01,120
what is t prime?

1076
00:48:01,120 --> 00:48:03,120
Incidentally,

1077
00:48:03,120 --> 00:48:07,120
x, of course, is equal to vt.

1078
00:48:07,120 --> 00:48:10,120
So really all I need to know is t,

1079
00:48:10,120 --> 00:48:14,120
and the velocity of the moving observer,

1080
00:48:14,120 --> 00:48:16,120
is the moving observer,

1081
00:48:16,120 --> 00:48:19,120
his trajectory is x equals vt,

1082
00:48:19,120 --> 00:48:21,120
here's t,

1083
00:48:21,120 --> 00:48:24,120
and here's x equals vt.

1084
00:48:24,120 --> 00:48:28,120
What is the time read by the clock

1085
00:48:28,120 --> 00:48:31,120
moving from here to here?

1086
00:48:31,120 --> 00:48:33,120
What is t prime?

1087
00:48:33,120 --> 00:48:35,120
Well, now that's easy to find out.

1088
00:48:35,120 --> 00:48:39,120
t prime squared minus x prime squared

1089
00:48:39,120 --> 00:48:43,120
must equal t squared minus x squared.

1090
00:48:43,120 --> 00:48:44,120
What are t,

1091
00:48:44,120 --> 00:48:46,120
sorry, this should be prime,

