t prime squared minus x prime squared

1093
00:48:49,120 --> 00:48:53,120
should equal t squared minus x squared for this point.

1094
00:48:53,120 --> 00:48:54,120
Why?

1095
00:48:54,120 --> 00:48:58,120
Because the expression for proper time is invariant.

1096
00:48:58,120 --> 00:49:01,120
Same expression in either reference frame

1097
00:49:01,120 --> 00:49:05,120
for the proper time between this point and the origin.

1098
00:49:05,120 --> 00:49:07,120
What do I know about this point?

1099
00:49:07,120 --> 00:49:09,120
I know that it's x prime is equal to zero,

1100
00:49:09,120 --> 00:49:11,120
so let's cancel that out.

1101
00:49:11,120 --> 00:49:14,120
No, let's not cancel that out, let's just rewrite it.

1102
00:49:14,120 --> 00:49:21,120
t prime squared equals t squared,

1103
00:49:21,120 --> 00:49:24,120
but now at this point, x is equal to vt.

1104
00:49:24,120 --> 00:49:31,120
So that's minus v squared t squared.

1105
00:49:31,120 --> 00:49:32,120
Well, that's interesting.

1106
00:49:32,120 --> 00:49:36,120
We now have a simple formula for t prime.

1107
00:49:36,120 --> 00:49:38,120
First of all, let's write that as

1108
00:49:38,120 --> 00:49:42,120
one minus v times t squared.

1109
00:49:42,120 --> 00:49:44,120
One minus v squared.

1110
00:49:44,120 --> 00:49:48,120
Times t squared.

1111
00:49:48,120 --> 00:49:50,120
Well, we just take the square root.

1112
00:49:50,120 --> 00:49:55,120
t prime, the time read by the moving clock,

1113
00:49:55,120 --> 00:50:00,120
is equal to the time read by the stationary clock.

1114
00:50:00,120 --> 00:50:03,120
The time read by the stationary clock

1115
00:50:03,120 --> 00:50:06,120
is just this time here,

1116
00:50:06,120 --> 00:50:11,120
times one minus square root of one minus v squared.

1117
00:50:11,120 --> 00:50:14,120
That's the famous formula of time dilation.

1118
00:50:14,120 --> 00:50:17,120
That when you see a moving clock,

1119
00:50:17,120 --> 00:50:19,120
that moving clock will appear

1120
00:50:19,120 --> 00:50:21,120
to move a little bit slow.

1121
00:50:21,120 --> 00:50:22,120
Why slow?

1122
00:50:22,120 --> 00:50:25,120
Because one minus v squared is less than one.

1123
00:50:25,120 --> 00:50:27,620
But everybody will agree about

1124
00:50:27,620 --> 00:50:30,120
the value of the proper time

1125
00:50:30,120 --> 00:50:32,120
between these two points,

1126
00:50:32,120 --> 00:50:34,120
although they will disagree

1127
00:50:34,120 --> 00:50:36,120
about the actual coordinate times.

1128
00:50:36,120 --> 00:50:41,120
In particular, the coordinate time t prime,

1129
00:50:41,120 --> 00:50:43,120
seen in the moving reference frame,

1130
00:50:43,120 --> 00:50:45,620
will be the coordinate time

1131
00:50:45,620 --> 00:50:48,120
in the stationary reference frame

1132
00:50:48,120 --> 00:50:51,120
times square root of one minus v squared.

1133
00:50:51,120 --> 00:50:54,120
So what that says is that the moving observer,

1134
00:50:54,120 --> 00:50:58,120
well, the stationary observers,

1135
00:50:58,120 --> 00:51:02,120
will see the moving clock run a little bit slow.

1136
00:51:02,120 --> 00:51:04,120
We really should at this point put

1137
00:51:04,120 --> 00:51:06,120
in the speeds of light, c squared.

1138
00:51:06,120 --> 00:51:09,120
v squared over c squared is

1139
00:51:09,120 --> 00:51:12,120
typically a very, very small number.

1140
00:51:12,120 --> 00:51:17,120
So this is almost t prime equals t,

1141
00:51:17,120 --> 00:51:20,120
but with a slight discrepancy.

1142
00:51:20,120 --> 00:51:23,120
This is the time dilation of a moving clock.

1143
00:51:23,120 --> 00:51:27,120
Now, how can it possibly be that we have relativity,

1144
00:51:27,120 --> 00:51:29,120
which says there's a complete parallel between,

1145
00:51:29,120 --> 00:51:31,120
or a complete symmetry,

1146
00:51:31,120 --> 00:51:35,120
between the moving observer and the stationary observer.

1147
00:51:35,120 --> 00:51:37,120
How do we then account for the fact

1148
00:51:37,120 --> 00:51:41,120
that the stationary observer sees the moving observer

1149
00:51:41,120 --> 00:51:44,120
having his time slowed down?

1150
00:51:44,120 --> 00:51:45,620
What does that mean if we

1151
00:51:45,620 --> 00:51:47,120
look at it the other way?

1152
00:51:47,120 --> 00:51:48,620
What does the moving observer

1153
00:51:48,620 --> 00:51:50,120
see about the stationary observer?

1154
00:51:50,120 --> 00:51:55,120
Does he see the stationary observer's time sped up?

1155
00:51:55,120 --> 00:51:56,120
No.

1156
00:51:56,120 --> 00:51:59,120
Also sees the time slowed down.

1157
00:51:59,120 --> 00:52:02,120
So if I move past you with my clock,

1158
00:52:02,120 --> 00:52:04,120
my clock seems to slow

1159
00:52:04,120 --> 00:52:06,120
down as far as you're concerned.

1160
00:52:06,120 --> 00:52:08,120
On the other hand, if I watch one of you,

1161
00:52:08,120 --> 00:52:11,120
and I have all of my fellow's,

1162
00:52:11,120 --> 00:52:14,120
lined up with me forming a reference frame,

1163
00:52:14,120 --> 00:52:17,120
they will also see your clock go slow.

1164
00:52:17,120 --> 00:52:18,120
How can that possibly be?

1165
00:52:18,120 --> 00:52:20,120
That sounds contradictory.

1166
00:52:20,120 --> 00:52:24,120
Well, they're talking about two different things.

1167
00:52:24,120 --> 00:52:27,120
The moving observer,

1168
00:52:27,120 --> 00:52:30,120
remember that the moving observer,

1169
00:52:30,120 --> 00:52:33,120
his time,

1170
00:52:33,120 --> 00:52:36,120
or his lines along which time are constant,

1171
00:52:36,120 --> 00:52:39,120
are not these horizontal lines here.

1172
00:52:39,120 --> 00:52:41,120
They're lines which look like this.

1173
00:52:41,120 --> 00:52:46,120
This is t prime equals a constant.

1174
00:52:46,120 --> 00:52:49,120
This is t prime equals a constant, and so forth.

1175
00:52:49,120 --> 00:52:53,120
So the lines on which t prime are constant

1176
00:52:53,120 --> 00:52:56,120
are different than the lines on which t are constant.

1177
00:52:56,120 --> 00:53:00,120
This is this relativity of synchronicity,

1178
00:53:00,120 --> 00:53:03,120
the relativity of being synchronous.

1179
00:53:03,120 --> 00:53:06,120
Different observers call different things synchronous.

1180
00:53:06,120 --> 00:53:10,120
Now, let's take the moving observer here,

1181
00:53:10,120 --> 00:53:14,120
and the moving observer looks

1182
00:53:14,120 --> 00:53:17,120
at the stationary clocks

1183
00:53:17,120 --> 00:53:20,120
at an instant of his time,

1184
00:53:20,120 --> 00:53:23,120
and asks, what does the stationary clock read?

1185
00:53:23,120 --> 00:53:26,120
Well, an instant of his time

1186
00:53:26,120 --> 00:53:30,120
looks like this.

1187
00:53:30,120 --> 00:53:32,120
So he's really asking

1188
00:53:32,120 --> 00:53:36,120
not what the stationary clock reads at this point,

1189
00:53:36,120 --> 00:53:39,120
but what the stationary clock reads at that point.

1190
00:53:40,120 --> 00:53:44,120
So there are two different questions.

1191
00:53:44,120 --> 00:53:46,120
When you ask

1192
00:53:46,120 --> 00:53:49,120
what one observer sees of the other one's clock,

1193
00:53:49,120 --> 00:53:52,120
there is a complete symmetry.

1194
00:53:52,120 --> 00:53:54,120
Let's see how to say this.

1195
00:53:54,120 --> 00:53:56,120
I think I've already said it,

1196
00:53:56,120 --> 00:53:59,120
but let's try to say it more clearly.

1197
00:53:59,120 --> 00:54:01,120
We're comparing different things.

1198
00:54:01,120 --> 00:54:05,120
The surfaces along which t is constant

1199
00:54:05,120 --> 00:54:07,120
and along which t prime is constant

1200
00:54:07,120 --> 00:54:08,120
are different surfaces,

1201
00:54:08,120 --> 00:54:10,120
and so when you ask whether a clock

1202
00:54:10,120 --> 00:54:12,120
is synchronous or not synchronous,

1203
00:54:12,120 --> 00:54:13,120
and so forth,

1204
00:54:13,120 --> 00:54:15,120
you have to account for this difference

1205
00:54:15,120 --> 00:54:16,120
in what you mean by synchronous.

1206
00:54:16,120 --> 00:54:18,120
That's all.

1207
00:54:18,120 --> 00:54:21,120
So that's the time dilation,

1208
00:54:21,120 --> 00:54:24,120
the fact that moving clocks appear

1209
00:54:24,120 --> 00:54:27,120
to stationary observers to go slow,

1210
00:54:27,120 --> 00:54:30,120
and stationary clocks appear

1211
00:54:30,120 --> 00:54:34,120
to moving observers also to go slow.

1212
00:54:34,120 --> 00:54:37,120
We could have been certain from the beginning

1213
00:54:37,120 --> 00:54:40,120
that whatever one observer sees

1214
00:54:40,120 --> 00:54:43,120
of the other's clock,

1215
00:54:43,120 --> 00:54:45,120
that they will be reciprocal

1216
00:54:45,120 --> 00:54:46,120
because of the reciprocal nature

1217
00:54:46,120 --> 00:54:49,120
of Lorentz transformations.

1218
00:54:49,120 --> 00:54:55,120
Okay, that's the slowing down of clocks.

1219
00:54:55,120 --> 00:54:57,120
Let's talk about the twin paradox.

1220
00:54:57,120 --> 00:54:59,120
Somebody asked me about the twin paradox.

1221
00:54:59,120 --> 00:55:01,120
We're now in a good position

1222
00:55:01,120 --> 00:55:04,120
to do the twin paradox

1223
00:55:04,120 --> 00:55:07,120
and see what it says.

1224
00:55:07,120 --> 00:55:09,120
Let's work it out.

1225
00:55:10,120 --> 00:55:20,120
The twin paradox,

1226
00:55:20,120 --> 00:55:22,120
two twins are born

1227
00:55:22,120 --> 00:55:24,120
at the origin of coordinates.

1228
00:55:24,120 --> 00:55:26,120
One stays home,

1229
00:55:26,120 --> 00:55:28,120
that means stays at rest,

1230
00:55:28,120 --> 00:55:29,120
doesn't move,

1231
00:55:29,120 --> 00:55:30,120
doesn't accelerate,

1232
00:55:30,120 --> 00:55:31,120
doesn't move at all,

1233
00:55:31,120 --> 00:55:33,120
and just moves along a trajectory like that,

1234
00:55:33,120 --> 00:55:35,120
a world line like that.

1235
00:55:35,120 --> 00:55:38,120
The other one is shot out

1236
00:55:38,120 --> 00:55:40,120
at a high velocity

1237
00:55:40,120 --> 00:55:42,120
not quite the velocity of light,

1238
00:55:42,120 --> 00:55:44,120
at a high velocity

1239
00:55:44,120 --> 00:55:46,120
for a certain period,

1240
00:55:46,120 --> 00:55:48,120
and then at the end of that period

1241
00:55:48,120 --> 00:55:51,120
turns around and comes back

1242
00:55:51,120 --> 00:55:54,120
and meets the twin

1243
00:55:54,120 --> 00:55:56,120
at that point there.

1244
00:55:56,120 --> 00:55:58,120
They compare their clocks.

1245
00:55:58,120 --> 00:56:01,120
Well, all kinds of clocks they could compare.

1246
00:56:01,120 --> 00:56:02,120
Their clocks, their watches,

1247
00:56:02,120 --> 00:56:04,120
their heartbeats,

1248
00:56:04,120 --> 00:56:05,120
their aging rate,

1249
00:56:05,120 --> 00:56:08,120
their metabolic time differences

1250
00:56:08,120 --> 00:56:10,120
between here and here,

1251
00:56:10,120 --> 00:56:12,120
how long their beards are,

1252
00:56:12,120 --> 00:56:13,120
or whatever,

1253
00:56:13,120 --> 00:56:15,120
whatever corresponds to a good clock.

1254
00:56:15,120 --> 00:56:18,120
They compare their clocks at this point

1255
00:56:18,120 --> 00:56:20,120
and ask what the relationship

1256
00:56:20,120 --> 00:56:23,120
between the time read by a clock moving here

1257
00:56:23,120 --> 00:56:25,120
and the time read by a clock moving here.

1258
00:56:25,120 --> 00:56:27,120
Well, we're all set up to calculate it now

1259
00:56:27,120 --> 00:56:29,120
because all we have to do

1260
00:56:29,120 --> 00:56:31,120
is to calculate the proper time

1261
00:56:31,120 --> 00:56:33,120
between this point and this point

1262
00:56:33,120 --> 00:56:35,120
along the vertical trajectory

1263
00:56:35,120 --> 00:56:37,120
and the proper time along this,

1264
00:56:37,120 --> 00:56:40,120
uh, trajectory

1265
00:56:40,120 --> 00:56:42,120
which consists of two different pieces.

1266
00:56:42,120 --> 00:56:44,120
We just add up the proper time

1267
00:56:44,120 --> 00:56:45,120
from here to here

1268
00:56:45,120 --> 00:56:47,120
and the proper time from here to here,

1269
00:56:47,120 --> 00:56:49,120
and that will tell us what the clocks measure.

1270
00:56:49,120 --> 00:56:51,120
Clocks measure proper time.

1271
00:56:51,120 --> 00:56:53,120
All right, first of all, this triangle,

1272
00:56:53,120 --> 00:56:55,120
assuming that the observer,

1273
00:56:55,120 --> 00:56:57,120
that the second twin comes back

1274
00:56:57,120 --> 00:57:00,120
with the same velocity that he was shot out with,

1275
00:57:00,120 --> 00:57:02,120
with some velocity v,

1276
00:57:02,120 --> 00:57:06,120
then this triangle is a nice isosceles triangle

1277
00:57:06,120 --> 00:57:07,120
and the second triangle

1278
00:57:07,120 --> 00:57:09,120
is a vertical triangle.

1279
00:57:09,120 --> 00:57:12,120
And we can divide this vertical line in half,

1280
00:57:12,120 --> 00:57:14,120
call this side t,

1281
00:57:14,120 --> 00:57:16,120
this half side t.

1282
00:57:16,120 --> 00:57:19,120
It takes, therefore, time to t

1283
00:57:19,120 --> 00:57:21,120
in the ref-

1284
00:57:21,120 --> 00:57:24,120
from the, uh, stationary person here,

1285
00:57:24,120 --> 00:57:26,120
it takes time to t

1286
00:57:26,120 --> 00:57:29,120
to go from this world point to this world point,

1287
00:57:29,120 --> 00:57:32,120
and therefore, the person who stays home

1288
00:57:32,120 --> 00:57:35,120
says it took a amount of time twice capital T

1289
00:57:35,120 --> 00:57:36,120
for my twin to return.

1290
00:57:36,120 --> 00:57:39,120
All right, so that's twice capital T.

1291
00:57:39,120 --> 00:57:42,120
That's what the observer who stays home

1292
00:57:42,120 --> 00:57:44,120
says the time interval

1293
00:57:44,120 --> 00:57:47,120
between birth and meeting the twin is.

1294
00:57:47,120 --> 00:57:48,620
Now, what about the twin

1295
00:57:48,620 --> 00:57:50,120
who goes out and comes back?

1296
00:57:50,120 --> 00:57:53,120
Let's, uh, calculate what the total proper time

1297
00:57:53,120 --> 00:57:55,120
is along this trajectory here.

1298
00:57:55,120 --> 00:57:58,120
He goes out with velocity v.

1299
00:57:58,120 --> 00:58:01,120
How far out does he get?

1300
00:58:01,120 --> 00:58:04,120
He gets out a distance v times t.

1301
00:58:04,120 --> 00:58:05,120
All right.

1302
00:58:05,120 --> 00:58:08,120
v times t is the distance

1303
00:58:08,120 --> 00:58:10,120
along the x-axis

1304
00:58:10,120 --> 00:58:12,120
that the moving twin gets out.

1305
00:58:12,120 --> 00:58:16,120
So this point, then, has coordinates

1306
00:58:16,120 --> 00:58:18,120
x equals vt

1307
00:58:18,120 --> 00:58:20,120
and time t.

1308
00:58:20,120 --> 00:58:22,120
Let's calculate the proper time

1309
00:58:22,120 --> 00:58:23,120
from here to here.

1310
00:58:23,120 --> 00:58:24,120
The proper time,

1311
00:58:24,120 --> 00:58:26,120
the square of the proper time,

1312
00:58:26,120 --> 00:58:29,120
is t squared minus x squared.

1313
00:58:29,120 --> 00:58:30,620
So the proper time along the

1314
00:58:30,620 --> 00:58:32,120
first leg of the journey here

1315
00:58:32,120 --> 00:58:34,120
is t squared

1316
00:58:35,120 --> 00:58:39,120
minus v squared t squared,

1317
00:58:39,120 --> 00:58:42,120
which is equal to 1 minus v squared

1318
00:58:42,120 --> 00:58:45,120
times t squared.

1319
00:58:45,120 --> 00:58:48,120
That's the square of the proper time.

1320
00:58:48,120 --> 00:58:50,120
We have to take the square root of it

1321
00:58:50,120 --> 00:58:53,120
to find out how much the clock

1322
00:58:53,120 --> 00:58:55,120
changed from here to here.

1323
00:58:55,120 --> 00:58:57,120
And so the time change, the proper time

1324
00:58:57,120 --> 00:59:00,120
along this trajectory here is square root

1325
00:59:00,120 --> 00:59:03,120
of 1 minus v squared times t.

1326
00:59:03,120 --> 00:59:05,120
What about on the second leg of the journey?

1327
00:59:05,120 --> 00:59:07,120
The second leg of the journey

1328
00:59:07,120 --> 00:59:11,120
is exactly parallel to the first leg of the journey,

1329
00:59:11,120 --> 00:59:13,120
except going backward.

1330
00:59:13,120 --> 00:59:15,120
The proper time between here and here

1331
00:59:15,120 --> 00:59:17,120
is exactly the same as the proper time

1332
00:59:17,120 --> 00:59:19,120
between here and here.

1333
00:59:19,120 --> 00:59:21,120
There's the same x coordinate

1334
00:59:21,120 --> 00:59:23,120
and the same t.

1335
00:59:23,120 --> 00:59:26,120
So the answer for the observer

1336
00:59:26,120 --> 00:59:29,120
going along this bent trajectory here

1337
00:59:29,120 --> 00:59:31,120
is twice this.

1338
00:59:31,120 --> 00:59:35,120
Twice t times square root of 1 minus v squared

1339
00:59:35,120 --> 00:59:41,120
as opposed to just twice t.

1340
00:59:41,120 --> 00:59:43,120
Which one is smaller?

1341
00:59:43,120 --> 00:59:46,120
The smaller one, the smaller proper time,

1342
00:59:46,120 --> 00:59:49,120
is associated with the twin

1343
00:59:49,120 --> 00:59:52,120
who got shot out and came back.

1344
00:59:52,120 --> 00:59:54,120
Why? Because 1 minus v squared

1345
00:59:54,120 --> 00:59:56,120
is smaller than 1.

1346
00:59:56,120 --> 00:59:58,120
So the amount of time read off

1347
00:59:58,120 --> 01:00:00,120
by the moving clocks here

1348
01:00:00,120 --> 01:00:03,120
is smaller by factor square root

1349
01:00:03,120 --> 01:00:05,120
of 1 minus v squared

1350
01:00:05,120 --> 01:00:08,120
than the time measured along

1351
01:00:08,120 --> 01:00:11,120
the trajectory of the twin who stayed home.

1352
01:00:14,120 --> 01:00:16,120
All kinds of times,

1353
01:00:16,120 --> 01:00:18,120
as I said, the length of a beard,

1354
01:00:18,120 --> 01:00:20,120
the number of heartbeats,

1355
01:00:20,120 --> 01:00:22,120
all sorts of things,

1356
01:00:22,120 --> 01:00:24,120
the time read along this moving trajectory

1357
01:00:24,120 --> 01:00:26,120
will be less,

1358
01:00:26,120 --> 01:00:28,120
and the consequence is that the moving

1359
01:00:28,120 --> 01:00:31,120
twin comes back looking younger,

1360
01:00:31,120 --> 01:00:33,120
feeling younger, looking younger, being younger

1361
01:00:33,120 --> 01:00:35,120
than the twin who stayed home.

1362
01:00:35,120 --> 01:00:37,120
Now, is this a paradox?

1363
01:00:37,120 --> 01:00:39,120
It's not a paradox,

1364
01:00:39,120 --> 01:00:41,120
because there's nothing inconsistent about it.

1365
01:00:41,120 --> 01:00:43,120
Doesn't look inconsistent.

1366
